# Notion Project Ops Rule

## Purpose
- Use Notion as the operational system for project documentation, issue tracking, decisions, and changelog.
- Apply this to all meaningful workstreams: new features, refactors, bugs, operational tasks, and long multi-step work.
- Keep repository files as the source of truth for code and technical implementation details.

## Canonical Notion structure (Option B)
- Maintain these databases:
  - `Projects`
  - `Issues`
  - `Initiatives`
  - `Docs`
  - `Decisions`
  - `Changelog`
- Every `Issue`, `Initiative`, `Doc`, `Decision`, and `Changelog` entry must relate to a `Project`.

## Required issue fields
- `Title`
- `Status` (`Backlog`, `Next`, `In Progress`, `Blocked`, `Done`)
- `Area` (for example: `Frontend`, `Backend`, `DB`, `API`, `Auth`, `Infra`, `UI`)
- `Priority` (`Low`, `Medium`, `High`)
- `Project` (relation)
- Optional but recommended: `Effort` (`S`, `M`, `L`), `Link`, `Created`
- For multi-step work, add `Initiative` relation and manage progress with initiative-filtered views.

## Agent workflow
- Determine project identity from root `package.json` `name` first (for example, `eve.apexapps.gg`).
- Use folder/repo name only as fallback when package name is missing.
- When user asks for project context, check Notion first for current `Project`, open `Issues`, and recent `Decisions`.
- When creating or refining a plan (feature, refactor, bug, migration), record or update corresponding `Issues` in Notion.
- When a meaningful technical choice is made, create/update a `Decision` entry with: context, options, chosen, why, tradeoffs, follow-ups.
- Keep `Changelog` entries short and outcome-focused.
- If a task has many steps or is expected to span multiple sessions, track it in Notion rather than only in chat context.
- If user shares a new feature idea, create an `Issue` entry (or doc note) so it is not lost.

## Sync policy (Notion vs repo)
- Notion stores planning/coordination artifacts (status, tasks, decisions, change log).
- Repo stores implementation artifacts (code, migration files, runbooks tightly coupled to code).
- If both are updated in the same session, keep them aligned before concluding work.

## Safety
- Do not delete or bulk-archive Notion pages/databases unless user explicitly asks.
- If Notion data conflicts with codebase reality, report the conflict and ask the user which source to treat as authoritative.
